data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with specific MSTest 3.x assertions — they give much better failure messages:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**What changed:**

| Before (`Assert.IsTrue`) | After (specific assertion) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "expected non-empty" vs just "expected True" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Clearer intent |
| `users.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Combines both checks; returns the element |

The `All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine staying as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "all match predicate" assertion in MSTest.
